f=Engineering/nova/custom/mobile-app-architecture/SKILL.md · in=mobile-app-architecture nova structures mobile app stays maintainable across platform's peculiarities app lifecycle, navigation, state, platform channels, two-OS reality. framework-specific mechanics (Flutter widgets/state, React Native, native) live dated playbook (ops's volatility-split pattern); architecture discipline invariant. nova **dormant default** skill activates business actually mobile app (`mobile_active`). · p=Mobile apps rot differently web: lifecycle bugs (state lost backgrounding), navigation spaghetti, platform-channel leaks, constant iOS/Android divergence. clear architecture state management, navigation structure, platform-abstraction boundaries keeps app understandable grows across two platforms. · wu=Triggers (only `mobile_active`): "build mobile app," "app architecture," "state management," "navigation," "platform channel," "iOS Android behavior," any mobile app structure work. · st:/ Protocol=`[GATE: mobile_active? — if false, nova is dormant; direct to mia (web) instead] \· A mobile app to structure \· -> STATE: a clear state-management approach (per the dated playbook's framework) \· -> NAVIGATION: a structured router, not ad hoc push/pop; deep-link-able \· -> LIFECYCLE: handle background/foreground/kill; persist what must survive` · in=**Check switch first.** `mobile_active` false, nova dormant business web-only work routes mia. Don't build mobile scaffolding business app (tempo's dormant pattern). **State management clear approach.** Pick apply one state pattern (per playbook's framework) consistently mixed hoc state mobile bugs breed. State survive backgrounding/kill persisted explicitly. **Structured navigation.** router named routes deep-linkability, scattered push/pop calls navigation large apps become unmaintainable deep links (and their security) live. **Lifecycle explicit.** Handle background, foreground, kill; classic mobile bug state silently lost backgrounds app. What survive persisted (offline-sync-discipline). **Platform channels behind abstractions.** Native integrations (camera, notifications, secure storage) sit behind clean interface; platform channel leaking through app maintainability security concern (secure storage especially aegis). **Two OSes, handled explicitly.** iOS Android differ (permissions, back button, lifecycle, conventions); handle differences deliberately, don't assume one behaves like other. dated playbook records current framework's cross-platform specifics. · of=`## Mobile Architecture: [app/feature] — [mobile_active ✓] \· State: [approach per playbook] \· Navigation: [router, deep-linkable] \· Lifecycle: [background/foreground/kill handled \· persisted state] \· Platform channels: [native integrations behind abstraction ✓ \· leaks: none/flagged] \· Two-OS: [differences handled explicitly] \· Playbook: [dated ref]` · pr=**Check mobile_active first** dormant web-only businesses; route mia., **One state approach, applied consistently** mixed hoc state breeds bugs., **Structured, deep-linkable navigation** scattered push/pop., **Lifecycle explicit** background/kill loses state unless you persist it., **Platform channels behind clean abstractions** leaks maintainability security concerns., **Two OSes handled explicitly** never assume iOS Android. · f=`mobile_active` false dormant; state route mia; build nothing., dated playbook framework architecture discipline runs framework-neutral; write playbook first real build (ops's platform-playbook pattern)., Cross-platform framework can't something natively platform-channel native behind abstraction, documented; don't fake cross-platform. · b:with Other Skills=**nova-config's `mobile_active`**: dormant switch gating entire agent., **app-store-release-discipline mobile-verification offline-sync-discipline** (siblings): release, test, data layers app., **mia**: web frontend; shares atlas's tokens raj's API contracts platform allows coordinate, don't duplicate., **